<subSubSection id="C300650BE84F5842FF52AD59FEC1FEE6" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="342" pageId="9" pageNumber="341" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA53680E84F5841FF52AD59FBD7F92C" blockId="9.[144,1105,771,1678]" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">
Distribution (
<figureCitation id="13212A05E84F5841FEEBAD59FEE6FAEC" box="[297,382,1331,1357]" captionStart="Fig.18" captionStartId="16.[181,214,848,870]" captionTargetBox="[255,1068,258,829]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[256,1066,259,827]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig.18. Central African distribution of Congomochtherus lobatus Oldroyd, 1970 (Note: N. Nigerian record not a precise place)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1472914/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
), phenology (
<tableCitation id="C698033BE84F5841FDDEAD59FDEAFAEC" box="[540,626,1331,1357]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[616,691,204,225]" captionTargetBox="[197,1115,280,622]" captionTargetId="graphics@4.[181,1141,268,629]" captionText="TABLE 1 Phenology of Congomochtherus species. Months - starting from July." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF656608E842584CFDAAA8A6FC4BFEA3" pageId="9" pageNumber="341" tableUuid="DF656608E842584CFDAAA8A6FC4BFEA3">Table 1</tableCitation>
) and biology: The species was originally described from Nigeria (no precise locality recorded), DR Congo and Tanzania. 
<bibRefCitation id="EF8B4B71E84F5841FBCFAD39FEC1FA2C" pageId="9" pageNumber="341" refId="ref10603" refString="LONDT, J. G. H. &amp; TSACAS, L. 1987. The genus Congomochtherus Oldroyd, 1970 (Diptera, Asilidae, Asilinae). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (N. S.) 23 (1): 29 - 42." type="journal article">Londt and Tsacas (1987)</bibRefCitation>
added Cameroon to this list while the only new record known to me is from Uganda. Specimens of this species are remarkably data deficient. Not a single specimen label has any information relating to habitat occupied. Looking at the records from the water-rich, tropical DRC provides little insight into habitat preference as all the places mentioned are near major or minor rivers and streams. Baraka is perhaps the most interesting locality as the centre is found not too far from Lake Tanganyika, giving rise to the thought that the species may be found along the banks of this and other major African lakes. The record from Cameroon features part of the fairly large centre of Yaoundé. Google Earth shows a substantial stream passing through Nkolbison and
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA53680E84C5842FF77A8A7FEC1FEE6" blockId="10.[181,1142,204,327]" pageId="10" pageNumber="342">so it is tempting to believe that the specimen came from this stream. The record from Uganda is for a forested area well supplied with water, and so again the likelihood of an association with a stream is high. It appears that the species may be associated with forest streams.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
